{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/opioid-dependence/background-information/prevalence/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"d7f47150-a2c5-57f9-88aa-5353f86fc58a","slug":"prevalence","fullItemName":"Prevalence","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 2aeab13b-25bd-45f1-b6ce-a74d00938ef2 --><h2>How common is it?</h2><!-- end field 2aeab13b-25bd-45f1-b6ce-a74d00938ef2 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 54974a3d-6812-485e-8677-a74d00938dbc --><!-- begin field 1dc15907-af9a-4cbb-b5cc-a74d00938ef2 --><ul><li>Approximately 9.0% of adults aged 16–59 years have taken an illicit drug in the last year and 3.5% have taken a Class A drug.</li><li>The proportion of young adults (aged 16–24 years) reported as taking illicit drugs in the past year is approximately 19.8%.</li><li>The prevalence of drug dependence varies with age, sex, employment status and ethnicity. <ul><li>It is more common in men (4.3%) than women (1.9%) and highest in men aged 16-24 years (11.8%).</li><li>In men, signs of drug dependence are most common in those classed as economically inactive (9.6%). For women, the highest prevalence is also found in those who were unemployed (4.4%).</li><li>The proportion of people showing signs of drug dependence (for drugs other than cannabis) in the last year was:<ul><li>1.9% in Black/Black British people.</li><li>1.1% in Asian/Asian British people.</li><li>0.8% White British people.</li><li>0.6% White other people.</li></ul></li></ul></li><li>In 2017/18 268,390 individuals were in contact with drug and alcohol services in England, with the largest proportion of them (53% or 141,189 people) in treatment for opioid dependence. </li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/opioid-dependence/references/\">NHS Digital, 2018</a>]</p><!-- end field 1dc15907-af9a-4cbb-b5cc-a74d00938ef2 --><!-- end item 54974a3d-6812-485e-8677-a74d00938dbc -->","topi